- Since this holds for all `x ∈ s`, we have `s ⊆ Set.f (Set.g s)`
- For the reverse, take `x ∈ Set.f (Set.g s)`. This means `x ∈ image g (image f s)`
- So there exists some `y ∈ image f s` such that `g y = x`
- `y ∈ image f s` means `f y ∈ s`
- Since `g y = x`, and `f` and `g` are inverses, we have `y = f x`
- So `f y = f (f x) = x`
- Therefore, `x ∈ s`
- So `Set.f (Set.g s) ⊆ s`
- Together, we have `Set.f (Set.g s) = s`
- This shows `Set.f ∘ Set.g = id`

